post_text:
If you have changed your router in the past few years, you most likely have an additional network with a 5G at the end. The 5G WIFI is much faster but, unfortunately, has a shorter range.

The best solution is to connect the school and work devices to the 5G while connecting all other devices (streaming, gaming, tablets, smart home devices, phones) on the non-5G network. Consider moving your router closer to the school/work devices to bring those important devices within range of the 5G network.

Read more Tech Tips on the Technology Page of the Virtual Learning Playbook at www.ccps.org.

post_text: Each school will be a distribution site beginning 9/1. Meals will be distributed based upon eligibility like they would typically be during the school year. post_text: Thirty-six seniors from Cecil County Public Schools (CCPS) are being awarded the 2020 Maryland Seal of Biliteracy. This distinguished award recognizes a student’s high level of proficiency in listening, speaking, reading, and writing in English and in one or more other languages. shared_text:
Children's Mental Health Matters
April 13 at 12:03 PM ·

We're heading into week 3 of Mental Health Monday. During this public health crisis, it’s common to feel a lot of stress and anxiety. In addition to the tragic loss of life, health, and income, we’re experiencing the loss of our daily routines.

But many of us are grieving. Grief can be a strong, and sometimes overwhelming emotion, but it’s a natural reaction to loss.

This week, we are providing resources for your families to help cope with the big feelings that come with the 5 stages of grief. We hope that you find them useful and that you remember to reach out for help if you find yourself, or your child, struggling. 💚

https://www.childrensmentalhealthmatters.org/resources/mentalhealthmondays/

#MentalHealthMonday #CMHMMaryland #ChildrensMentalHealthMatters

post_text: This morning a parent came into the main office of Cecil Manor exhibiting symptoms of respiratory illness. In an effort to exercise an abundance of caution, Cecil Manor Elementary will dismiss at 11:45 today to allow time for the building to be cleaned, particularly the office area. As a reminder, there are currently NO confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Cecil County but we are going to be cleaning the building as a precautionary measure. At this time, we anticipate that the school will be open tomorrow but we will communicate as necessary if that changes. Please keep in mind that anyone exhibiting symptoms of illness should remain home.

The North East Middle School team has been named a Maryland State Winner in the Samsung Solve for Tomorrow Contest for its proposed plan to address bullying in our community!

The Samsung Solve for Tomorrow Contest encourages teachers and students to solve real-world issues in their community using classroom skills in science, technology, engineering and math (STEM).

North East Middle School is among the nation’s 100 State Winners (at least one school from all 50 states) and will receive $15,000 in technology for its achievement. Read more here:
http://ow.ly/FZZy50xQD1K

shared_text:
Perryville High School
December 12, 2019 at 9:03 PM ·

The PHS PLTW Biomedical Science Capstone students and the PHS STEM Academy Capstone students will be presenting their proposed capstone projects at the 2019 Topic Defense Poster Symposium on Wednesday December 18th from 5:00 - 6:30 pm in the PHS Media Center.

During this event, you will be able to meet one on one with Capstone students to discuss their proposed capstone projects. This will provide students an opportunity to answer questions and defend their proposed project. It will also allow students to get valuable feedback to help them further develop their project.

All are welcome to attend at any time between 5:00 - 6:30 pm.

Please contact Mr. Larry Sickels at lrsickels@ccps.org for more information.

Parents, students, CCPS employees, and community members are asked to provide feedback below.

post_text: It is with great sadness that we share the news of the sudden passing of Mrs. Valerie Morrison, English Language Arts teacher at Elkton High School. The crisis counseling team will be at the school on Monday. Our thoughts and prayers are with the Elkton High community and the family, friends, and students of Mrs. Morrison. She will forever be remembered as an outstanding educator who made a difference in the lives of students, colleagues, and the many who had the privilege to know her.

post_text: Beginning on Monday, November 18, middle and high schools will adjust their dismissal times for the remainder of this school year. On Monday, Tuesday, Thursday, and Friday - all middle and high school dismissal times will be 10 minutes earlier. Wednesday secondary dismissals will remain the same. Elementary dismissal schedules will remain the same. This modified schedule will allow for a more timely arrival of buses for the completion of afternoon routes for our elementary schools. Students received the following letter at school today and a copy will also be emailed to all parents. Read the full letter here: http://ow.ly/VV0950x1pzu

post_text: Elkton High School hosted the Spooktacular Fall Festival Saturday. The Drug Free Cecil Youth Coalition did an amazing job of planning and organizing the Trunk or Treat, the Health Fair, and the National Prescription Drug Take Back event. They also received a Presidential Proclamation for their work in advocating a drug-free message to their peers as well as for promoting healthy living for their school communities. The prevention message was heard loud and clear in Elkton on Saturday!

shared_text:
Maryland Center for School Safety
October 21, 2019 at 3:00 PM ·

UNITY DAY 2019 happens this week on October 23, 2019! Join us and together we can share one giant ORANGE message of hope and support showing that our world believes that no child should ever experience bullying.

The purpose of Unity Day is to demonstrate that we are united against bullying - acting together for kindness, acceptance and inclusion of all students.

What can you DO to be part of Unity Day?

1. Wear ORANGE - orange shirts or accents such as an orange tie, scarf, vest, necklace, or leggings!
2. Take pictures and share them on social media (be sure to tag us Maryland Center for School Safety and Maryland State Department of Education) using #UnityDay and #UnityDay2019.

Who can participate in Unity Day?

Individuals, schools, communities, and businesses can wear or display orange to show support for students who have been bullied.

We will be promoting this event on our social media channels and welcomes schools to share our posts.
